article.headline: WASHINGTON 114, MILWAUKEE 109 (OT)
article.story:
MILWAUKEE (AP)-- Larry Hughes was good in regulation, even better in overtime. Hughes scored a season-high 36 points, including the first eight in overtime, to lead the Washington Wizards to a 114-109 victory over the Milwaukee Bucks on Saturday night. "I was catching the ball where I wanted to catch it, and I was taking what they'd give me," Hughes said after shooting 13-of-22 from the field and 8-of-10 from the foul line. "I was pretty much locked in." Kwame Brown came off the bench for the first time this season and scored 18, including a tip-in that tied the game at 98 and forced overtime. Christian Laettner and Jarvis Hayes each had 11 as the Wizards snapped a nine-game losing streak in Milwaukee dating back to the 1998-99 season. Brown, who seemed unconcerned about starting the game on the bench, rescued the Wizards at the end of regulation when he tipped in Hughes' miss. "They had a small guy on me," Brown said. "I figured I could clear this guy out. I was fortunate to get it." Michael Redd had 28 points, and Desmond Mason added 19 for Milwaukee but missed 10 of 17 free throws. Rookie T.J. Ford had career highs of 16 points and 12 assists, and Damon Jones added a season-high 18 points. Hughes scored on a layup and hit a 21-foot jumper in overtime as the Wizards took a 102-98 lead. Hughes added four more points before fouling out with 1:21 left. Hughes was unstoppable in the second half and overtime. He scored 25 of the Wizards' 29 points over one stretch, capped by two free throws to make it 106-102 with 2:49 left in overtime. Hayes made a layup and Brown made a jumper that gave Washington a 110-102 lead with 39.3 seconds left. The Bucks hurt themselves by missing nine of 11 shots in the extra session and 14 free throws overall, including eight by Mason in the third quarter. "I don't know how many we missed, but it was a lot," Redd said. "That hurts us tonight. That was a big key for us." Washington missed 15 free throws, but they never came at crucial times like the Bucks' misses. Redd's four free throws down the stretch gave the Bucks a 98-94 lead with 35 seconds left. Hughes cut it to two with a layup. After a Bucks' timeout, Mason inbounded to Redd, who passed to Jones in the corner. He missed, and the Wizards got the ball and called timeout. When play resumed, 6-11 Brown got around the 6-3 Jones and tipped in Hughes' missed 3-point shot with 0.9 seconds left.

Game notes
Washington guard Steve Blake made his first career start. ... Jordan inserted Brown into the game with 3:21 left in the first quarter and the Wizards ahead 16-15. ... The Bucks placed F Toni Kukoc on the injured list Friday and signed F Dan Langhi. ... Milwaukee's Tim Thomas missed his sixth straight game with a sprained right ankle.
